pr_review_comment_body:
I don't really like the `init()` here, it just adds more burden on the binary boot. Why not simple have them all vars? like

```
var (
  bindAddr = flag.String("bind-addr", "localhost:6060", "address to listen for incoming HTTP requests")
)
```

@ajkavanagh

Another aside: This goes back to our "we use Juju and reactive in different ways" conversation. We started out building Tengu using a conventional config management tool (Chef), but switched to Juju because we needed a lot more complex orchestration behavior than what could be reasonably accomplished using Chef. In our first iteration, we only did the orchestration stuff in Juju and off-loaded all the config management stuff to Chef. So I'm looking at the reactive framework as a way to solve the orchestration issues because I think Chef and Puppet already solved the config mgmt issues.

From our discussions, it feels as if you're using Juju a lot more like conventional config management and you're looking at charms.reactive as a way to solve those issues. Stuff like idempotency etc. My view on that is that we shouldn't try to solve those issues in Charms.reactive because config mgmt tools already do that. Not reinventing the weel etc..

Ok, this is where things will probably start to get a bit confusing.

`KernelSpecsRef` gives you access to a collection of `KernelSpecs` each of which is identified by name.

Example lookup:

```js
function kernelSpec(kernelSpecsRef, kernelSpecName) {
  const kernelSpecs = kernelspecs.byRef[kernelSpecsRef];
  return kernelSpecs.byName[kernelSpecName];
}
```

Does that clarify it?
